  "formatedtext": "Leontine martyrs -  Leontine martyrs  The Leontine Martyrs were a group of people who were killed after a long period of captivity in Persia. They were executed by the order of King Yazdegerd II in 455, five years after the insurrection led by Vartan Mamikonian . The group is named after Leontius of Vanand (In Armenian \u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0562 \u0542\u0587\u0578\u0576\u0564, pronounced \"Surb Ghevond\"), the most senior of the religious group. Contents 1 Martyrs 1.1 Leontius of Vanand 1.2 Joseph I of Armenia 1.3 Sahak of Syunik Rshtuni 1.4 Tatik of Basen 1.5 Mushegh 1.6 Arshen 1.7 Samuel 2 Survivors 2.1 Abraham of Arazd 3 Veneration 4 References Martyrs [ edit ] This section needs expansion with: biographies of the names. You can help by adding to it . ( June 2019 ) Leontius of Vanand [ edit ] A high level priest also known as St. Ghevond (in Armenian \u054d\u0578\u0582\u0580\u0562 \u0542\u0587\u0578\u0576\u0564) Joseph I of Armenia [ edit ] Joseph I of Armenia or St. Hovsep I (in Armenian \u054d\u0562. \u0540\u0578\u057e\u057d\u0565\u0583 \u0531 \u0540\u0578\u0572\u0578\u0581\u0574\u0565\u0581\u056b), catholicos of Armenia (437\u2013452) Sahak of Syunik Rshtuni [ edit ] Sahak of Syunik Rshtuni (in Armenian \u054d\u0561\u0570\u0561\u056f \u0565\u057a\u057d. \u054c\u0577\u057f\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0575\u0561\u0581) - a  bishop Tatik of Basen [ edit ] Tatik of Basen (in Armenian \u0532\u0561\u057d\u0565\u0576\u0575\u0561\u0581 \u0539\u0561\u0569\u056b\u056f \u0565\u057a\u056b\u057d\u056f\u0578\u057a\u0578\u057d) - a bishop Mushegh [ edit ] Mushe or Mushegh (in Armenian \u0544\u0578\u0582\u0577\u0565\u0572 \u0584\u0561\u0570\u0561\u0576\u0561\u0575) - A priest Arshen [ edit ] Arshen (in Armenian \u0531\u0580\u0577\u0565\u0576 \u0565\u0580\u0565\u0581) - a priest Samuel [ edit ] Samuel (in Armenian \u054d\u0561\u0574\u0578\u0582\u0567\u056c \u0584\u0561\u0570\u0561\u0576\u0561\u0575) - a priest Plus a number of deacons Survivors [ edit ] Abraham of Arazd [ edit ] Abraham of Arazd was an Armenian priest and a disciple of the Leontine martyrs. Like his teachers, he was subjected to prolonged torture , but unlike them, was eventually set free. He afterward left society to become a hermit , remaining one until his death in the 5th century. He is regarded as a saint by the Armenian Church , with a feast day of December 20. Veneration [ edit ] St. Ghevond the Priest and His Companions are commemorated as saints in the Armenian Apostolic Church . The day of the Feast of St. Ghevond the Priest and His Companions is July 31. It is also considered the day of the clergy in the Armenian Church and their office is celebrated on the Tuesday after the western Sexagesima , as they are regarded as the patron saints of the Armenian clergy. References [ edit ] Holweck, F. G. A Biographical Dictionary of the Saints . St. Louis, MO: B. Herder Book Co. 1924. This article about a saint is a stub . You can help  by expanding it . v t e This biographical article about an Armenian religious figure is a stub . You can help  by expanding it . v t e Retrieved from \" https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Leontine_martyrs&oldid=902016126 \" Categories : 455 deaths Armenian saints Deacons Martyred groups Lists of saints 5th-century Christian saints Saints of the Armenian Apostolic Church Persian Armenians Saint stubs Armenian religious biography stubs Hidden categories: Articles to be expanded from June 2019 All articles to be expanded Articles using small message boxes Year of birth missing All stub articles Navigation menu Personal tools Not logged in Talk Contributions Create account Log in Namespaces Article Talk Variants Views Read Edit View history More Search Navigation Main page Contents Current events Random article About  Contact us Donate  store Contribute Help Community portal Recent changes Upload file Tools What links here Related changes Upload file Special pages Permanent link Page information Cite this page Wikidata 